On Indigenous Peoples' Day, President Joe Biden recognizes and celebrates the contributions and resilience of Indigenous peoples in the United States. He acknowledges that the country has not fully lived up to its promise of equality and opportunity for all, especially when it comes to upholding the rights and dignity of Indigenous people. The President reaffirms the Federal Government's trust and treaty obligations to Tribal Nations and commits to supporting a future grounded in Tribal sovereignty and respect for the human rights of Indigenous people. He emphasizes the importance of consultation with Tribal officials and making respect for Tribal sovereignty the cornerstone of Federal Indian policy. President Biden acknowledges the significant sacrifices made by Native peoples throughout history and their ongoing contributions to the nation. He urges everyone to celebrate and recognize the Indigenous communities and cultures that make up the United States. The President proclaims October 11, 2021, as Indigenous Peoples' Day and calls upon the people of the United States to observe the day with appropriate ceremonies and activities.